AB  - General trust is the extent to which one expects extended social-network members to act with goodwill toward oneself, and it exhibits notable individual differences. A recent evolutionary hypothesis posits that low general trust facilitates disease avoidance and that the behavioral immune system (BIS) thus regulates general trust. Previous studies supported this disease-avoidance hypothesis of general trust by finding significant negative correlations between measures of trait-level BIS activation (e.g., pathogen-disgust sensitivity) and general trust with cross-sectional samples. However, these cross-sectional correlations might be spurious due to omitted variables and conflated if bidirectional effects exist between trait-level BIS activation and general trust. In this research, we leveraged a Chinese panel dataset, which included measures of subjective likelihood of contracting contagious diseases and general trust, to test the disease-avoidance hypothesis of general trust more stringently. We found that subjective likelihood of contracting contagious diseases did not predict trust in most people or trust in neighbors in first-difference models, which eliminate unobserved heterogeneity. Subjective likelihood of contracting contagious diseases also did not predict trust in most people or trust in neighbors in cross-lagged models, which control for time lags. These findings provide no evidence that subjective likelihood of contracting contagious diseases as a different measure of trait-level BIS activation than pathogen-disgust sensitivity relates to general trust.
